First City Monument Bank Limited (FCMB) has announced it will be issuing N20 billion Series one Commercial Paper (CP). FCMB Group Plc in a release on the Nigerian Stock Exchange (NSE) signed by the company secretary, Olufunmilayo Adedibu notified the investing public that one of its subsidiaries First City Monument Bank is undertaking its inaugural Commercial Paper Issuance under its N100 billion CP programme. The release stated that the CP has a tenor of 269 days with the aim of raising up to N20 billion to support the Bank’s short-term funding needs, saying that the CP serves as an additional funding source for the Bank. Commercial paper is an unsecured, short-term debt instrument issued by a corporation, typically for the financing of accounts payable and inventories and meeting short-term liabilities. Maturities on commercial paper rarely range longer than 270 days. Commercial paper is usually issued at a discount from face value and reflects prevailing market interest rates. In 2017, FMDQ Securities Exchange Plc approved the registration of the First City Monument Bank (FCMB) Limited N100 billion Commercial Paper (CP) Programme on its platform. With the registration of this CP programme, FCMB will be able to easily raise short-term finance from the debt capital markets (DCM), within its respective programme limit, to support its business operations as at when required in the future. According to FMDQ, the approval is well in line with its aspiration to support institutional growth and stimulate continuous development of the Nigerian economy at large. Meanwhile, the Group’s result for the 2019 financial year had revealed that the bank’s gross earnings rose by five per cent from N177.2bn in the 2018 financial year to N186.7bn in 2019. Its net interest income was up by six per cent from N72.6bn in 2018 to N77.3bn in 2019, while net fee and commission income was down by four per cent from N21.6bn to N20.8bn. The bank’s impairment charges were down by 34 per cent to N9.3bn in 2019 from N14.1bn in 2018.